<Link id="l00868" /><CodeLine lineNumber="868"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Visit a type entry. CheckPointer is true if the type has</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00869" /><CodeLine lineNumber="869"><Highlight kind="comment">/// one of its predecessors as one struct/union member. SeenPointer</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00870" /><CodeLine lineNumber="870"><Highlight kind="comment">/// is true if CheckPointer is true and one of its predecessors</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00871" /><CodeLine lineNumber="871"><Highlight kind="comment">/// is a pointer. The goal of CheckPointer and SeenPointer is to</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00872" /><CodeLine lineNumber="872"><Highlight kind="comment">/// do pruning for struct/union types so some of these types</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00873" /><CodeLine lineNumber="873"><Highlight kind="comment">/// will not be emitted in BTF and rather forward declarations</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00874" /><CodeLine lineNumber="874"><Highlight kind="comment">/// will be generated.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00875" /><CodeLine lineNumber="875"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="keywordtype">void</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> BTFDebug::visitTypeEntry(</Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">const</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/ditype">DIType</a> &#42;Ty, uint32&#95;t &amp;TypeId,</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00877" /><CodeLine lineNumber="877"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="keywordflow">if</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> (!Ty || DIToIdMap.find(Ty) != DIToIdMap.end()) &#123;</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00879" /><CodeLine lineNumber="879"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00880" /><CodeLine lineNumber="880"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// To handle the case like the following:</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00881" /><CodeLine lineNumber="881"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">//    struct t;</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00887" /><CodeLine lineNumber="887"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">//    struct s2 &#123; &#95;t c; &#125;</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00888" /><CodeLine lineNumber="888"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">//    int test2(struct s2 &#42;arg) &#123; ... &#125;</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00889" /><CodeLine lineNumber="889"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">//</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00890" /><CodeLine lineNumber="890"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// During traversing test1() argument, &quot;&#95;t&quot; is recorded</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00891" /><CodeLine lineNumber="891"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// in DIToIdMap and a forward declaration fixup is created</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00892" /><CodeLine lineNumber="892"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// for &quot;struct t&quot; to avoid pointee type traversal.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00893" /><CodeLine lineNumber="893"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">//</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00894" /><CodeLine lineNumber="894"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// During traversing test2() argument, even if we see &quot;&#95;t&quot; is</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00896" /><CodeLine lineNumber="896"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// bring in types for &quot;struct t&quot;. Otherwise, the &quot;struct s2&quot;</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00897" /><CodeLine lineNumber="897"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// definition won&#39;t be correct.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00898" /><CodeLine lineNumber="898"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">//</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00899" /><CodeLine lineNumber="899"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// In the above, we have following debuginfo:</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00900" /><CodeLine lineNumber="900"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">//  &#123;ptr, struct&#95;member&#125; -&gt;  typedef -&gt; struct</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00903" /><CodeLine lineNumber="903"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">//  &#123;different types&#125; -&gt; &#91;various derived types&#93;+ -&gt; another type.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00904" /><CodeLine lineNumber="904"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// For example,</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
